Big Query

I will be querying for the word hurricane from September 15th 2015 - October 15th 2015. This was the year when hurricane Joaquin destroyed my home and island so Im curoius about the New York Times coverage of that.

term <- "hurricane" # Need to use + to string together separate words
begin_date <- "20150915"
end_date <- "20151015"

#construct the query url using API operators
baseurl <- paste0("http://api.nytimes.com/svc/search/v2/articlesearch.json?q=",term,
                  "&begin_date=",begin_date,"&end_date=",end_date,
                  "&facet_filter=true&api-key=","mIFzdD9Pmlmb2hMFkZTol7ObtrmKYlQp",
                  sep="")

#examine our query url
baseurl
## [1] "http://api.nytimes.com/svc/search/v2/articlesearch.json?q=hurricane&begin_date=20150915&end_date=20151015&facet_filter=true&api-key=mIFzdD9Pmlmb2hMFkZTol7ObtrmKYlQp"
#this code allows for obtaining multiple pages of query results 
initialQuery <- fromJSON(baseurl)
maxPages <- round((initialQuery$response$meta$hits[1] / 10)-1) 

pages <- list()
for(i in 0:maxPages){
  nytSearch <- fromJSON(paste0(baseurl, "&page=", i), flatten = TRUE) %>% data.frame()
  message("Retrieving page ", i)
  pages[[i+1]] <- nytSearch 
  Sys.sleep(6) 
}

nytDat %>% 
  group_by(response.docs.type_of_material) %>%
  summarize(count=n()) %>%
  mutate(percent = (count / sum(count))*100) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(y=percent, x=response.docs.type_of_material, fill=response.docs.type_of_material), stat = "identity") + coord_flip()

nytDat %>%
  mutate(pubDay=gsub("T.*","",response.docs.pub_date)) %>%
  group_by(pubDay) %>%
  summarise(count=n()) %>%
  filter(count >= 2) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_bar(aes(x=reorder(pubDay, count), y=count), stat="identity") + coord_flip()

clean_tokens_headline <- str_remove_all(tokenized_headline$word, "[:digit:]") #remove all numbers

clean_tokens_headline <- gsub("s", '', clean_tokens_headline)

tokenized_headline$clean <- clean_tokens_headline

tokenized_headline %>%
  count(clean, sort = TRUE) %>%
 #illegible with all the words displayed
  mutate(clean = reorder(clean, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, clean)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(y = NULL)

#remove the empty strings
tib_headline <-subset(tokenized_headline, clean!="")

#reassign
tokenized_headline <- tib_headline

#try again
tokenized_headline %>%
  count(clean, sort = TRUE) %>%
  filter(n > 2) %>% 
  mutate(clean = reorder(clean, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(n, clean)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(y = NULL)

The biggest difference between the tokenized paragram and the tokenized headlines is the switch between ship and joaquin. This is unsurprising however because during Hurricane Joaquin, a cargo ship, El Faro, sank off the coast of The Bahamas and no passengers survived. The frequencies in the words did change however with paragraphs ahving hurricanes appear over 30 times but headlines only saw hurricane appear over 15 times. This would be due to the increased amount of content in a paragraph when comapring that with a headline.
